Pitts is a top-ten tight-end option with huge upside this week. He could walk away from Week 7 with a top-three tight end game.

Freiermuth is quietly having a breakout season as the TE9 in fantasy points per game. He's ninth in target share, seventh in target per route run rate, and fifth in air yard share. He leads all tight ends with seven deep targets while sitting at 15th in red zone looks. Freiermuth ranks sixth in PFF receiving grade and yards per route run (minimum ten targets). He gets a solid matchup against Miami, who is 25th in DVOA while ranking 13th in receiving yards and first in catch rate allowed. Freiermuth is a top-ten tight end.

In Weeks 1-5, Tonyan had a 12.2% target share with a mediocre 53.3% route run rate. Last week those numbers increased to 27.3% and 75.5%. Could this be the beginning of heavier usage from Green Bay? Possibly. It could also be an anomaly. Only time will tell. After last week's explosion, Tonyan is the TE11 overall, more of a reflection of the position. That's only his second game this season inside the top 12 in weekly fantasy scoring. Tonyan has seen fruitful usage in the red zone with five targets (eighth). He's 11th in PFF receiving grade and eighth in yards per route run (minimum 15 targets). The matchup is ok, with Washington ranking 21st in DVOA with the 12th-highest yards per reception but second-lowest catch rate and only one receiving touchdown allowed. Tonyan is a borderline TE1.

Hurst finds himself inside the top-12 tight ends this season (TE12) which is more of a statement of the position than a ringing endorsement for Hurst. Hurst does have three distinct feathers in his cap that we look for in tight ends with high route participation (76.0%, 10th), red-zone involvement (fifth in red-zone targets), and a plus matchup. Atlanta is second in receptions and third in receiving yards allowed to the position. Hurst is a TE1.

Engram has bumbled and stumbled his way to TE19 in fantasy points per game despite ranking 11th in target share, 13th in route participation, 11th in routes run, and sixth in deep targets. The sad thing is that his athleticism doesn't translate to being good as a tight end. He's 26th in PFF receiving grade, 20th in yards per route run, and 18th in YAC per reception (minimum 15 targets). New York is a decent matchup for Engram to retain low-end TE1/TE2 status. The Giants have allowed the 11th-highest catch rate, fourth-most receptions, and fifth-most receiving yards to tight ends.

Hill is slowly on his way to debunking my disdain for his positional eligibility, as he's up to 31 snaps as a receiver (35 at QB). Hill remains stalled at 3.6 routes per game with only one reception for the year. Hill is the TE5 for the year, thanks to two massive outings. In the other three games, he finished as the TE50, TE16, and TE28. He's averaging 5.3 rushes and 53.2 rushing yards per game which is skewed by his 112-yard performance. Hill has three games with 35 or more rushing yards. He's tied with Kamara with five red zone rushing opportunities. He is a weekly home run swing or whiff at the tight end position.

Every week we have 1-2 games that fall into the Friday injury update bucket, with a total overhaul coming late in the week. This game falls into that bucket. Schultz was a late inactive last week. His outlook could change drastically due to his health and whether Prescott returns or not. Over his final two games, he's seen four total targets. Over that span, I'm tied with Schultz with receiving yards earned (zero).

After playing a part-time role for much of the season, Bellinger saw his snap rate jump to 96.8% and his route run rate climb to 81.2%. He drew a 20% target share with an end zone target and 1.46 yards per route run. Overall this season, he's fourth in PFF receiving grade, 13th in yards per route run, and fourth in YAC per reception (minimum 15 targets). Jacksonville is 20th in DVOA and sixth in yards per reception allowed to tight ends. Bellinger is a TE1/high-end TE2.

Henry has now stacked three consecutive weeks above 80% snaps. Since Week 4, he's seen a 22.2% target share (5.3 targets per game) with a 71.1% route run rate, 2.17 yards per route run, and four red zone targets. Chicago is 19th in DVOA against tight ends ranking 21st in yards per reception and 25th in receiving yards allowed. Henry is a low-end streaming option / TE2.

Gesicki is coming off a big game, but this isn't a week to go back to him if you have better options. He's seen his involvement in the offense tick up, with a 12.3% target share and 67.9% route run rate over the last three games (three red zone targets). Over that stretch, his efficiency has still been uninspiring, with 1.37 yards per route run. He's a TE2 this week against a Steelers defense that's a longstanding no-fly zone for tight ends. They are fourth in DVOA with the eighth-lowest catch rate and only one touchdown allowed.

Flip a coin. Pick a name out of a hat. That's how it feels attempting to pick which SEA tight end to play weekly. Fant leads Dissly with a 12.4% target share, but their route run rate and red zone usage are nearly identical. Fant is ninth in PFF receiving grade and 16th in yards per route run facing off against a defense ranked 23rd in DVOA against tight ends. Los Angeles has the tenth-lowest catch rate permitted, but they are also third in yards per reception allowed. Fant is a dice roll streamer.

In his first NFL game, Dulcich saw a 12% target share playing 71% of the snaps with a 79.4% route run rate. He secured two of his three targets with 44 receiving yards and a score. The Jets have allowed the 11th-highest yards per reception and seventh-highest receiving yards per game (zero tds) to tight ends. Dulcich is a high-end TE2 who could sneak into the top 12 this week.

Dissly is 15th in PFF receiving grade and 11th in yards per route run among tight ends (minimum ten targets) with the same plus matchup. If Fant is rostered, then your streamer decision is easy with Dissly. Dissly has three games this season as a top-eight fantasy tight end. In the other three weeks, he was TE28 or lower.

The Cole Kmet experiment isn't worth bothering with this week. Not against New England, who is fifth in DVOA against the position allowing the 13th-lowest receiving yards and fifth-lowest catch rate. Kmet has surpassed 20 receiving yards only twice this season.
The fall came fast for Conklin. He's no longer worthy of a roster spot. Since Week 5, he's averaged 1.5 targets per game with a 42.2% route run rate.

Alie-Cox is a matchup-based streaming candidate. Since Week 4, he has led the Indy tight end rotation with a 9.3% target share, 33.7 receiving yards per game, and a 51.1% route run rate. The last time these two teams met, Alie-Cox crushed this defense, securing all six of his targets for 85 receiving yards and two scores. Tennessee is 31st in DVOA, sixth in receptions per game, and fourth in receiving yards allowed per game to tight ends.

Cam is a DL1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against an Arizona Cardinals offense allowing the ninth most fantasy points per game to the position. Things could get ugly if Jordan gets it going early enough. Start Cam with confidence.
Maxx has been elite this season and checks in as a top-five DL option despite a neutral matchup against the Houston Texans.
Josh Allen looks primed to explode against a New York Giants offense allowing the 14th most fantasy points to the position. Allen is a DL1/LB2 option for Week 7.

Sweat stayed hot in Week 6, tallying three solos, three assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Sweat, who had zero sacks coming into Week 5, now has three sacks in his last two games. Sweat is a DL1 option when he is clicking, and it looks like he is finally doing just that. It should go without saying that he should be rostered universally now that he is finally playing like the Montez that established himself as one of the league's premier pass rushers again. He is more DL2 than DL1 for Week 7, as the Commanders defensive front has a tough on-paper matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Bosa is optimistic that he will play this weekend against Kansas City. He may see his snaps slightly scaled back but is still a DL1 option against the Chiefs. Kansas City has allowed the 13th most fantasy points to the defensive end position.

Kayvon recorded his first career sack against Lamar Jackson, finishing Week 6 with three solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Dogged with effort concerns throughout the pre-draft process, Kayvon showed he has a high motor and can give second efforts on his strip sack in the closing moments of the Giants win. Kayvon is the most toolsy of this year's pass rushers and should start to show why he was in the mix to be the first player off the board this spring on a more consistent basis now that he has the first sack under his arm. Treat him as an upside DL2 option in what amounts to a revenge game against the Jaguars in Week 7. You can bet Kayvon will be going just a little harder to prove to the Jags that they made the wrong decision by passing him up with the number one overall pick.

Davenport appears to be on the verge of a breakout and gets a soft offensive line in Week 7 against the Arizona Cardinals. Arizona has allowed the ninth most fantasy points to the defensive end position. Treat Davenport as a DL2 option for Week 7.
Jaelan's struggles continue. He is too talented to drop in deeper leagues but with bye week crunches now upon us, his spot on your roster should be evaluated. He is a DL4 option at best for Week 7.

Rasheem is in line for an increased snap count in Week 7 due to Jonathan Greenard being sent to IR. There is still a three man rotation with Jerry Hughes and Mario Addison, but all three now have DL3 upside despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Ebiketie has just one sack on the season and has been a disappointment since his NFL debut, but things are trending in the right direction at the perfect time for fantasy managers. Ebiketie played 82 percent of the snaps in Week 6, tallying three solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. It was his highest snap and solo count of the season, and if he continues to play over 70 percent of the snaps, he becomes an instant DL3 option. Ebiketie was a popular name in dynasty leagues and even redraft circles due to his perceived open path to heavy snaps. It may have taken six weeks to materialize, but it appears that we will finally start to see a return on investment from the rookie edge rusher. Treat him as a DL3 with DL2 upside for a plus matchup against a Cincinnati Bengals team allowing the 11th most fantasy points to the position.
Jihad is set to take on an expanded role in Week 7 due to Azeez Ojulari and Oshane Ximines being ruled out vs. the Jaguars. Jihad has some DL3 appeal during the bye week.

Hughes has slowed down after a hot start that saw him record four sacks in his first three games. He is still a DL3 option during the byes and will see an expanded role with Jonathan Greenard being placed on IR. Start him where needed.

Lewis was excellent in Week 7, recording three solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He saw the most snaps of the reserves with Kwity Paye ruled out and should maintain his snap share in Week 7 due to his success against the Jaguars. Tyquan is a sneaky DL3 play against a Titans team allowing the second most fantasy points to opposing edge rushers.

Drake has been excellent this season, his three sacks tie him for the lead among all rookies. He posted three solos and a sack last week and now has three sacks in his last four games. The prevailing thought was that his role would continue to expand with both Nick Bosa and Arik Armstead sidelined, especially after he played 45 percent of the snaps in Week 5. Unfortunately, Drake actually played a season-low 21 percent of the snaps in Week 6 while seeing Kerry Hyder and Kemoko Turay both see more snaps than him. His talent is obvious, so he should see a permanent role expansion sooner rather than later, but until then, he is going to be hard to trust as more than a DT3/DL5 option. 21 percent of the snaps is simply too low to allow us to trust his usage, even if he has been getting to the quarterback consistently. Keep him benched until the 49ers finally turn him loose.

Zaire has been a man on a mission this season and is an LB1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Tennessee Titans. The LB7 overall on the season, Zaire should be trusted as an LB1 option while Shaq Leonard remains sidelined.

Demario beasted in Week 6, racking up seven solos, two assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Davis is a high-end LB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a struggling Arizona Cardinals offense surrendering the 14th most fantasy points to the position.

Rashaan was excellent in Week 6, racking up seven solos, five assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. The former first round pick has had his peaks and valleys this season but has graded out as an LB2 option through six games. He has been producing with and without Mykal Walker in the lineup and is an elite LB3 with LB2 upside during the byes going forward.

Zaven Collins was a beast in Week 6, racking up an insane five solos, four assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and a pass defended. Unfortunately, Collins was listed as a limited participant on Monday's estimated practice report, making him questionable at best for Thursday Night Football. Regardless of whether or not they give him rest on the short week or not, Zaven is someone who needs to be rostered and started universally. He oozes with LB1 upside but will stay relegated to the LB2 realm until he proves he can be more consistent. With that said, if the Cardinals continue to let him rush the passer (he already has more blitzes than last year), it will only be a matter of time until he bullies his way into the LB1 conversation. Start Collins as a strong LB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a New Orleans Saints team allowing the fifth most fantasy points to the position.

The roller coaster ride known as the Patrick Queen experience is not for the faint of heart. Queen was excellent in Week 6, tallying five solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He has been one of the more consistent tacklers at his position, never seeing less than four solos but, unfortunately, never recording more than five. He has, however, been seeing consistent snaps and has forced his way into the LB2 conversation with some strong play. Queen has a sack or an interception in three of his last four games and is an LB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a Cleveland Browns team allowing the 15th most fantasy points to the position and dealing with injuries on the offensive line. Start Queen where possible.

Pratt should see a slight increase in snaps, but more importantly, increased tackle opportunities, with Logan Wilson set to miss at least a couple of games. Pratt checks in as a DB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Mykal Walker is expected to return to the lineup this weekend after missing Week 6 with a groin injury. Mykal will go right back to being an LB1 option while knocking Troy Andersen back to the waiver wire. Start Walker with confidence for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Jacob Phillips continues to impress, this time racking up four solos and six assists against the New England Patriots. Phillips has been excellent for IDP managers since taking over the every down role in the wake of the Anthony Walker injury, and it looks like he will be the one insulated from Deion Jones eventually factoring into the rotation. Phillips is a strong LB2 option going forward and will be just that for a Week 7 matchup against Lamar Jackson and the Baltimore Ravens.

Tied for second in the league with six sacks, Rashan Gary is in the midst of a career season. He was excellent again in Week 6, recording four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Rostered universally on other providers, Rashan still carries the LB-only designation at Yahoo. With that being said, it is well past time that fantasy managers add him to their Yahoo rosters as an LB2 option. Gary is going to hit double digits in sacks if he makes it through the season healthy and at his current pace, he should continue to push to be the NFL sack leader and a potential Defensive Player of the Year candidate. You don't leave this type of talent and production on waivers in competitive leagues. For reference, Alex Highsmith, who leads the NFL with 6.5 sacks and is also LB only on Yahoo, is rostered in 21 percent of leagues. This disparity should be addressed, especially since Rashan is the more talented player and the more likely one to keep up this level of production. Rashan has a terrific Week 7 matchup against a Washington Commanders team surrendering the second most fantasy points to opposing edge rushers. Start him with confidence as a DL1/LB1 option for this weekend.

Jamin Davis is seeing a role reduction for the Washington Commanders. Jamin played just 66 percent of the snaps in Week 6, recording three solos and one assist. He is losing box snaps to Darrick Forrest in three safety looks and has now played less than 66 percent of the snaps for two straight weeks. Yes, 66 percent is an improvement from the 53 percent he played in Week 5, but Jamin, who played 93 percent of the snaps in Week 1, loses a ton of his upside in a part time role as opposed to a full time one. Dripping with athletic gifts, it is hard not to be a fan of the young linebacker, but it has become apparent that he is not seeing a large enough role to warrant weekly consideration as anything more than an LB4 (or an LB3 during a heavy bye). Keep Jamin benched for Week 7 for a tough on-paper matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Losing snaps? Hold my beer. Cody Barton played just 39 percent of the snaps in Week 6 and may have officially lost his job in nickel packages. Ryan Neal is soaking up enough box snaps to make Barton surplus to requirements if he keeps proving to be a liability in coverage. Barton is an exciting, high tackle producer for IDP purposes, but stat stuffing alone will not keep you on the field in the NFL. Barton should see more snaps in Week 7, so we shouldn't see a repeat of the one solo and one assist line he posted last week, but Barton should no longer be considered a starting option, even during the byes. He stopped playing an every snap role back in Week 4, but no one could have envisioned that he would fall this far. Those in shallower formats should feel free to play the wire for a replacement. Those in deeper leagues or dynasty leagues should hold if bench sizes allow.

Quincy Williams was all over the field on Sunday, racking up eight solos and six assists in the upset win over the Green Bay Packers. Quincy returned from injury to play 81 percent of the snaps and should be back closer to 100 percent this weekend. Quincy was playing at a strong LB2 level before the injury and should be immediately reinserted back into that conversation after his strong showing in Week 6. Start him as a DB2 option for a neutral Week 7 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Bush played just 64 percent of the snaps in Week 6. He still had four assists and two solos but is going to be hard to trust during the byes if we cannot trust his weekly snap share. Treat him as a deep league LB4 only and keep him benched where possible.

The Cardinals continue to teach a master class on how to misuse an elite talent. Simmons continues to see an expanded role with Nick Vigil sidelined but still spent 44 percent of his snaps in the slot in Week 6. Give up on the Simmons dream until he is traded or the Cardinals get a new defensive coordinator.

The roller coaster ride known as the Patrick Queen experience is not for the faint of heart. Queen was excellent in Week 6, tallying five solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He has been one of the more consistent tacklers at his position, never seeing less than four solos but, unfortunately, never recording more than five. He has, however, been seeing consistent snaps and has forced his way into the LB2 conversation with some strong play. Queen has a sack or an interception in three of his last four games and is an LB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a Cleveland Browns team allowing the 15th most fantasy points to the position and dealing with injuries on the offensive line. Start Queen where possible.

Akeem Davis-Gaither is now an LB3 option, due to Logan Wilson slated to be sidelined for the next two to five weeks. ADG exploded for nine solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss back in Week 3 when he filled in for Germaine Pratt, proving that he has a fantasy-friendly game even when not seeing a near every snap role. He will likely see something close to the 69 percent of the snaps he saw when Pratt was sidelined this week against the Atlanta Falcons and should be able to parlay that into decent LB3 production. Treat him as just that for a neutral Week 7 matchup against the Falcons.

It sounds like Mykal Walker will be back for Week 6, which in turn will send Andersen back to playing reserve snaps. Rashaan Evans has been playing well enough that Andersen likely did not earn an expanded role when Walker was sidelined. Keep him stashed in deeper leagues, but Andersen can be dropped in shallower formats.

Jaylon Smith has been relatively quiet since his impressive outing in his Giants debut. Jaylon recorded five solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss in his first game with the Giants but has managed just four solos, five assists, and zero tackles for loss in the two games since then. Jaylon is a solid depth option in deeper leagues, but the LB3 with LB2 upside value he displayed in his debut is no more. He has yet to top 65 percent of the snaps, so perhaps he will become more consistent with extra playing time, but until then, Jaylon should be left on benches or even waiver wires. Look elsewhere for linebacker help for Week 7.

There is no word yet on Deion's status for Week 7, but when he does get the nod, expect him to start out as a reserve siphoning snaps from Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah and Sione Takitaki. Jones' future value will be tied to what type of role he is handed when he is back in game shape.

Baron is becoming a star for the Denver Broncos. He has played well enough to force a three man rotation on the edge when Randy Gregory returns and may have cost Bradley Chubb a contract with the Broncos this offseason. Baron now has 2.5 sacks in his last two contests after recording an impressive three solos, one sack, two tackles for loss, one interception, two passes defended, and one fumble recovery against the Los Angeles Chargers. He is a must-start DL option as long as he is hot and is a worthwhile LB2 play on Yahoo if you still happen to play IDP leagues there. Start him as a DL1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a New York Jets team surrendering the sixth most fantasy points to the position.

Uchenna continues to lead the Seahawks edge rushers in snaps week to week, and it is time to start taking him seriously. Up to three sacks on the season after recording three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss in Week 6, Nwosu makes for an excellent bye-week filler option. He has played 80 percent of the snaps in four of six weeks while seeing over 70 percent the other two weeks, putting him well ahead of Darrell Taylor and Boye Mafe, who are both sub-60 percent many weeks. Nwosu has DL3 value during the byes, and with two sacks in his last three games, he is getting hot at the perfect time for fantasy managers. Nwosu is a borderline DL2 option in a revenge game against a Los Angeles Chargers team surrendering the 11th most fantasy points to the position.

After crossing the 40 percent snap mark just once all season, Spillane saw 70 percent of the snaps in Week 6, tallying three solos, two assists, and one pass defended. They were using Spillane on third downs while giving Devin Bush the bulk of the early down work, situation-specific usage that may continue. The suggestion here is to take a wait-and-see approach, but Spillane is worth a speculative add.

Schobert could see his role increased coming out of the bye but is expected to play behind Dylan Cole once again with Zack Cunningham ruled out. However, he played just 16 percent of the snaps in Week 5 and could be left with another bit role this week. Keep him benched where possible due to snap uncertainty.

Samson was excellent in Week 6, recording five solos, three assists, and two tackles for loss against the Atlanta Falcons. Up to 3.5 sacks, Ebukam is in the midst of a career season and is seeing extra snaps with Arik Armstead on IR. He will still see around 70-80 percent of the snaps when Nick Bosa is healthy, so Ebukam is someone you want on your rosters during the byes. He has 2.5 sacks in his last three games and is peaking at the right time for the banged-up 49ers defensive front. Samson is a DL3 with DL2 upside for a plus Week 7 matchup against a Kansas City Chiefs team surrendering the 14th most fantasy points to opposing edge rushers.

Derwin remains locked in as a top-three option at defensive back for Week 7. He has been rolling lately and will look for his third consecutive DB1 finish against a divisional foe in the Seattle Seahawks. Expect Derwin to have another big game.

Winfield remains an elite option for Week 7 despite the tough on-paper matchup against a Panthers team limiting the position to the fourth-fewest fantasy points per game. Winfield is a must-start DB1 regardless of opponent, especially when he is this hot.

Sneed has been incredible this season, checking in as the DB1 overall and in points per game through six weeks of action. Ninth in the league in solo tackles with a whopping three sacks as a corner, Sneed is one of a kind. Do not hesitate to start him as a DB1 option until he cools down.
Talanoa is in concussion protocol, making his Week 7 status uncertain. He is a beast when healthy but fantasy managers should start to prepare to potentially be without their DB1 this weekend.

DeShon has been excellent in the Tracy Walker role and is the DB4 in points per game on the season. Treat him as a DB1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against a Dallas Cowboys team allowing the 14th most fantasy points to the position.

Curl was excellent in Week 6, recording five solos and one sack. Curl has been back in the lineup and producing for weeks, so it is time to start taking him seriously as a top-end DB2 option again. He is a DB1 option when he is at his best, and if this week is any indication, he should be able to get there within the next few weeks. Treat Curl as a borderline DB1 option for a tasty Week 7 matchup against a Green Bay Packers team, gifting the second most fantasy points per game to the safety position.

Jaquan was at it again in Week 6, tallying two solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Brisker has been producing at a DB1 level this season, checking in as the DB22/S14 through six weeks of play. Brisker now has two sacks in his last three games, displaying the versatility that has him pegged for the DB1 conversation for years to come. Treat him as a DB1 option for an excellent Week 7 matchup against a New England Patriots team surrendering the sixth most fantasy points to the position. Jaquan should be started in all competitive leagues.

Dugger is back to his regular role and responded with six solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. A forgotten man after getting injured and being eased back into his role upon his return, Dugger is a DB1 option when he is seeing starters snaps and needs to be started universally. Start him as a DB2 with DB1 upside for a plus matchup against Justin Fields and a Chicago Bears offense allowing the 11th most fantasy points to the position.
Tariq has been on fire for the Seahawks and is riding a six game interception streak. He makes enough tackles to be a DB3, but his pick upside puts him squarely in the CB1/DB2 conversation.

Rayshawn Jenkins is heating up. Jenkins followed up the seven solos and five assists he recorded in Week 5 with a seven solo, one assist, and one pass defended performance against the Indianapolis Colts. He is producing at a high-end DB2 level and should be counted as just that for a plus matchup against a New York Giants team surrendering the 9th most fantasy points to the safety position.
Deablo is a DB1/LB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Houston Texans. Houston allows the 11th most fantasy points to the linebacker position.

Ryan Neal is catching fire. He recorded six solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one pass defended, and one forced fumble in Week 6 against the Arizona Cardinals and is quickly becoming one of the better DB2 options. He could be in the DB1 discussion with another strong week or two, so fantasy managers need to act now to avoid disappointment. Neal has replaced Josh Jones in the Jamal Adams role in this defense and should be put in position to be one of the top options at the position going forward. Neal is a strong DB2 option for a neutral Week 7 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Forrest has earned a regular role on defense, one that comes with some valuable box snaps, but is going to be hard-pressed to offer more than deep league flex2 value for fantasy managers at his current snap rate. Keep him benched during Week 7 where possible.

Keanu Neal has been one of the most frustrating IDP players to roster since he left Atlanta. From being used out of position on the Cowboys to being fourth on the depth chart in Tampa Bay, it has been a guessing game as to when Keanu will actually produce. Take last week, for example; Keanu plays 100 percent of the snaps but managed just three solos. In Week 4, Keanu suddenly played 58 percent of the snaps and tallied six solos after seeing a grand total of three defensive snaps over the first three weeks of the season. Keanu will be back to more of a part-time role this week with Mike Edwards expected back but is still a high-upside, low-floor DB3 option since Logan Ryan is on short-term injured reserve. Start Keanu as a DB3 option despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Geno Stone started in place of the injured Marcus Williams but did not see a full-time role as expected. Instead, he saw 75 percent of the snaps, while Kyle Hamilton jumped up to 45 percent. Stone should start in Week 7, but it may not be long before Hamilton evens the snaps. Treat Stone as a DB3 for Week 7 instead of a DB2.

Gipson will be a DB2 option if Talonoa Hufanga is forced to miss Week 7 due to still being in the league's concussion protocol. Gipson will likely take over the box role, with Odum taking on Gipson's role. He is safer to deploy as a DB3 with DB2 upside, but those in a double bye pinch can plug him as a DB2 where needed.
